00:02:57.190 --> 00:03:00.840
when the law is so broad that pretty much
everyone is a copyright infringer, people

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:04.769
stop paying attention to those laws. When
the laws fail to keep up with technology,

00:03:04.769 --> 00:03:08.019
it loses legitimacy, and we become a nation
of scofflaws.

00:03:08.019 --> 00:03:11.959
So to make copyright laws work in the digital
age, there have to be copyright exceptions

00:03:11.959 --> 00:03:16.690
and limitations. And there are. Fair use is
the most famous exception; we'll get to that

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:20.080
in a minute. But there are are also some more specific
exceptions and limitations we should look at.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:23.840
These exceptions cover a lot of different
uses, like reproduction of copyrighted works

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:27.950
for blind and disabled persons. They allow
libraries and archives to preserve, copy,

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:32.290
and distribute protected works. It also limits
libraries' liability when a patron uses the

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:37.159
copy machine to photocopy protected materials.
The first sale rule under Section 109 means

00:03:37.159 --> 00:03:41.330
that once a copyright owner sells you a legal
copy of a book or something, they no longer

00:03:41.330 --> 00:03:46.489
control the distribution rights of that particular
copy of the work. You, as the owner of a lawfully

00:03:46.489 --> 00:03:51.310
made copy may sell, rent, donate it, or whatever.
This is why libraries can loan you a book

00:03:51.310 --> 00:03:54.760
and what allows you to sell your books and
music to secondhand stores, if anyone does

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:59.520
that anymore. It's also what allows the three
remaining video stores in America to stay open.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.460
So this gives you the right to sell your books
and CDs, but you probably can't sell the digital

00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:07.250
music and books that you buy from Apple or
Amazon. The courts say that the first sale

00:04:07.250 --> 00:04:11.599
right applies only to the distribution right
and not the reproduction right. Since selling

00:04:11.599 --> 00:04:16.169
your MP3 collection would require making a
copy of those files, that is a no-no. As the

00:04:16.169 --> 00:04:20.959
law stands now, there is no legal secondary
market for digital works of any type.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:24.559
When you click on that purchase or buy button
you're really not "buying" a copy of the

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:27.889
work, you're entering into a type of licensing
arrangement. And that's fine. I mean that

00:04:27.889 --> 00:04:33.069
licensing agreement is in the Terms of Use,
which I'm sure you read- No? Didn't read it?

00:04:33.069 --> 00:04:36.610
Well, I'm sure you clicked 'accept' or even
'I understand and accept' when you created

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:40.619
your Apple or Google or Amazon account, so,
you're in the agreement.

00:04:40.619 --> 00:04:44.599
Some types of works like musical compositions
and sound recordings, for example, are subject

00:04:44.599 --> 00:04:49.430
to compulsory or statutory licenses for certain
uses. These licenses provide legal authorization

00:04:49.430 --> 00:04:53.039
to use a copyrighted work in certain ways
and for certain purposes, as long as the user

00:04:53.039 --> 00:04:56.659
pays the required fee and otherwise meets
the conditions in the law. The copyright owner

00:04:56.659 --> 00:04:59.469
can't deny you permission as long as you pay
up.

00:04:59.469 --> 00:05:03.020
This is how artists get away with covering
other artist's songs. They just pay the fee

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:05.889
noticed that cover versions of popular songs
are kind of a big deal on YouTube.

00:05:05.889 --> 00:05:10.059
Searching "Frozen cover" turns up about
2.8 million results. How does this work?

00:05:10.059 --> 00:05:14.119
"Frozen cover" turns up about 2.8 million
results. How does this work?

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:18.440
Well, in 2011 YouTube entered into an agreement
with several major music publishers to allow

00:05:18.449 --> 00:05:22.330
cover versions of songs to reside on the site,
with part of the advertising revenue going

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:26.479
to the original rights holders. So those are
a few of the specialized exceptions and limitations

00:05:26.479 --> 00:05:31.349
to copyright enforcement. But by far, the
broadest, most flexible, most controversial,

00:05:31.349 --> 00:05:34.389
and most famous copyright exception is fair
use.

00:05:34.389 --> 00:05:38.369
Courts have said the fair use defense allows
them to quote, "Avoid rigid application of

00:05:38.369 --> 00:05:42.509
the copyright statute when, on occasion, it
would stifle the very creativity which that

00:05:42.509 --> 00:05:46.469
law is designed to foster." Fair use acts
like a safety valve. It allows for certain

00:05:46.469 --> 00:05:49.869
socially beneficial uses that you might otherwise
get in trouble for.

00:05:49.869 --> 00:05:54.020
To paraphrase an 1841 court decision: "The
progress of learning advances when the law

00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:58.830
allows follow-on authors to bestow their intellectual
labor and judgment in reworking selections

00:05:58.830 --> 00:06:02.929
from a prior work, without prejudicing the
profits or prospects of that work." What?

00:06:02.929 --> 00:06:07.110
Who would say this? Y'know, Mark, I would
love to advance the progress of learning by

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:11.320
bestowing my intellectual labor and judgment
on the reworking of this prior work, but uh,

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:14.820
I just worry about prejudicing the profits
of the prospects of that work.

00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:19.119
Anyway, fair use is an affirmative defense,
which means the defendant must show and prove

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:23.339
that the use was fair and not an infringement.
The only way to definitively find out whether

00:06:23.339 --> 00:06:26.999
something is fair use is by having a judge
tell you it is. And this is a problem when

00:06:26.999 --> 00:06:30.969
taking a copyright case through trial costs
anywhere from $300,000 to a couple million

00:06:30.969 --> 00:06:34.279
dollars. Some courts have called the fair
use exception the most troublesome in the

00:06:34.279 --> 00:06:39.050
whole law of copyright. And they are not wrong.
I mean, the term fair use isn't defined in

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:43.250
the Copyright Act and courts have a lot of leeway
in how they decide if something is a fair use.

00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:47.059
Courts have to consider all the factual evidence
at hand for each particular case. And every

00:06:47.059 --> 00:06:50.830
case is different thanks to the huge variety
of copyrightable works and the many contexts

00:06:50.830 --> 00:06:56.229
in which these works can be used, like classroom
lessons, blog posts, YouTube videos, or in

00:06:56.229 --> 00:06:59.789
a project where the entire contents of a university
library are digitized.

00:06:59.789 --> 00:07:04.240
So how to decide. Courts use four factors
to determine whether a use is fair. The first

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:07.740
factor is the purpose and character of the
use. Like whether the use is commercial or

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:13.100
is for nonprofit educational purposes. Noncommercial
or educational uses weigh in favor of fair use.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:16.680
In the last twenty years courts have
expanded this factor to include consideration

00:07:16.689 --> 00:07:20.819
of whether the work is transformative. They
look at whether the use actually transforms

00:07:20.819 --> 00:07:24.869
the underlying purpose of the work by adding
a new meaning or message. Courts often hold

00:07:24.869 --> 00:07:29.300
that parody as a transformative fair use. Parody
functions as a critical commentary of the

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.119
original work. Courts have also recently held
that a project to digitize large collections

00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:37.559
of works and the making available of small segments
of texts from those works are transformative uses.

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:41.560
That makes the Google Books project
a fair use. That Google Books decision is

00:07:41.569 --> 00:07:44.629
currently in the appeals process though, so
it might not hold up.

00:07:44.629 --> 00:07:48.899
Publishers and authors will argue that merely
copying all these books without adding expression

00:07:48.899 --> 00:07:52.809
or value other than placing the work within
a highly commercialized digital ecosystem

00:07:52.809 --> 00:07:57.749
in a crass attempt to attract users, is not
transformative. Google tells a slightly different

00:07:57.749 --> 00:08:02.550
story. They'd say the project makes these
works searchable, discoverable, and universally

00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:06.619
accessible, and that that is a transformative
use with significant public benefit.

00:08:06.619 --> 00:08:10.459
The second factor has to do with the nature
of the copyrighted work. Courts have consistently

00:08:10.459 --> 00:08:14.479
held that the more original and creative a
work is, the more protection it's given from

00:08:14.479 --> 00:08:18.249
copying and it's less likely that a court
will find fair use. On the other hand, the

00:08:18.249 --> 00:08:22.369
more informational or functional the plaintiff's
work, the broader the scope of the fair use

00:08:22.369 --> 00:08:26.629
defense. In practice, this means that fictional
works tend to have a stronger copyright protection

00:08:26.629 --> 00:08:31.189
as they're works of imagination. They're basically
pure expression. Nonfiction works like news,

00:08:31.189 --> 00:08:35.169
biographies, and encyclopedias are filled
with uncopyrightable facts. This means they

00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:38.860
require less creativity to make and they're
granted less protection under copyright law.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:42.979
The third factor basically looks at how much
of the work you use, and there are two parts

00:08:42.979 --> 00:08:47.519
to this factor. The first is quantitative
substantiality. That looks at the amount of

00:08:47.519 --> 00:08:52.269
work you use, like how much of the video or
how many pages of the book. So wait a minute.

00:08:52.269 --> 00:08:55.949
How did we get so far into an episode about exceptions without rolling the Mongol-tage? Hit it!

