00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:33.350
The fourth factor addresses the effect of
the use on the potential market for, or value

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:36.910
of the copyrighted work. What we're looking
at here is whether the derivative work has

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:40.430
harmed the copyright owner's ability to make
money from the original. Courts try to weigh

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:44.250
any public benefit derived from the new use
with the personal gain the original owner

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:48.339
will receive if the use is prohibited. If
your use doesn't damage the original copyright

00:09:48.339 --> 00:09:51.679
owner's ability to make money, you don't
have to show a whole lot of public benefit.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:56.980
It's just hard to argue that you uploading Interstellar
to your YouTube channel has any public benefit.

00:09:56.980 --> 00:10:01.120
While these four factors are most often used
to determine fair use, courts can use any

00:10:01.129 --> 00:10:05.259
other factors that they deem relevant, including
broad considerations of whether the use will

00:10:05.259 --> 00:10:08.879
advance the public interest and the goals
of the Copyright Act. Unfortunately, this

00:10:08.879 --> 00:10:13.509
means that there is no clear formula for how
courts determine fair use. Fair use is designed

00:10:13.509 --> 00:10:18.129
to be a flexible tool, and any rule that's
flexible is necessarily unpredictable.

00:10:18.129 --> 00:10:21.939
Yet many people have argued that fair use
has become predictable in recent years.

00:10:21.939 --> 00:10:25.319
A string of court decisions have expanded
the meaning of what is considered to be a

00:10:25.319 --> 00:10:29.709
transformative fair use. Courts are carving
out policy-specific areas, like education

00:10:29.709 --> 00:10:33.540
where uses are pretty likely to be allowed.
User groups have published Best Practices

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:37.209
documents, many of which are available online;
we've got some links down below. Authors and

00:10:37.209 --> 00:10:40.579
publishers argue the courts have expanded
the breadth of fair use too far, and that these

00:10:40.579 --> 00:10:45.019
best practices guides are biased in favor of
expanding fair use. In the Supreme Court case

00:10:45.019 --> 00:10:50.739
Harper &amp; Row v The Nation, the majority opinion
coined what I like to call the Copyright Golden Rule.

00:10:50.740 --> 00:10:54.740
Take not from others to such an extent and
in such a manner that you would be resentful

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:58.620
if they so took from you. Thanks for watching.
